Abstract¶

To aid making property purchase decision, an exploratory analysis was performed on a dataset of property sale records from 2000 to 2021. General trends and aggregations were provided, with linear regression performed to reveal suburbs with highest property price growth rates.

With the extracted insights, it was revealed that while buying houses is more profitable, the median price in suburbs near CBD is generally unaffortable for my family. In contrast, houses located more than 35 km away from the CBD were priced comparably to units near CBD. It was therefore suggested that it may be more vaible to purchase a CBD unit for work convenience initially, and eventually trade it in for a house in the outskirts for retirement.

Introduction¶

This exploratory analysis was done as an overview of property price trend in Sydney, which would help my family (as new immigrants) to plan our potential future purchase.

First few sections serve as a general understanding of how the overall market behaves over the year, while in the later part of this analysis, focus was gradually shifted towards properties that best suit our needs.

Dataset¶

Data source: https://www.pricefinder.com.au/

This dataset was downloaded from PriceFinder as separated .xlsx files, which were then merged into a single SQLite database. The SQL database consists of 2 tables:

  1. records

    This table contains 731,552 property sales records, each record contains the following data:

    • id: unique identification of the sales record, formed by merging address, postcode and sale date
    • record_date: date of sale (from 2000-01-05 to 2022-01-04)
    • price: final sale price
    • sale_type: type of sale (Agents Advice - Sale, Normal Sale, Multi-Sale, Part Sale, Unknown)
    • prop_id: id of the property, formed by merging address and postcode
    • property_type: type of property (Commercial, Unit, Other, House, Vacant Land, Industrial)
    • bedrooms: number of bedrooms
    • bathrooms: number of bathrooms
    • carparks: number of car parks

  2. property

    This table contains 455,865 properties that have associated sales record(s), each property details consist of the following data:

    • address: address with postcode attached, act as unique identification
    • street: street name
    • locality: suburb name (844 suburbs in total)
    • postcode: postcode (312 in total)
    • land_area: land area

Data Cleaning¶

There is no missing values in both tables. For records, unusually high number of bedrooms, bathrooms and car parks were found, possibly due to the sales of buildings as a whole. Hence, for normal households, only properties with maximum 5 bedrooms/bathrooms and 3 car parks were considered.

On the other hand, it was noticed that some records show abnormally low prices. These records (specifically, all records with price less than $1,000) were removed from the analysis.

Also, to aid yearly aggregation, a year column was generated from record_date. It should be noted that only sales records on or before 2021-12-31 were considered to ensure accuracy of annual statistics.

Consequently, a combined dataset was then formed by merging the two tables with left join on records. The final dataset for analysis consists of 641,588 records (88% of available records).

Further analysis (Fig. 1) suggested that most records were Normal Sales of either House or Unit properties. For simplicity and sake of interest, only these records were considered.

For sale prices, a small portion of properties were sold in high values. To focus on properties in reasonable range, only records with sale price below \$3,000,000 were considered. The sale price distribution after filtering is shown in Fig. 2 above.

It was noted that although there were some high value sales, most of the sales were less than \$2,000,000.

In summary, the following criterias were applied:

  • sales record date: on or before 2021-12-31
  • number of bedrooms: 0 to 5
  • number of bathrooms: 1 to 5
  • number of car parks: 0 to 3
  • sale price: \$1,000 to \$3,000,000

The final dataset therefore contains 600,451 records (82% of the raw data).

Analysis¶

General price trend¶

General property price (Fig. 3) is trending upwards, median prices for House and Unit in 2021 were 1.3M and 0.8M respectively.

As shown in Fig. 4, from 2000 to 2021 (21 years), positive growths in median price for House and Unit were observed in 15 and 16 of the recorded years respectively. Meaning property price in general has been growing consistently.

Price trend by suburbs¶

To see how sale prices are affected by localities, median prices in 2021 of different suburbs were plotted against their distance from Sydney CBD:

Fig. 5 shows that, in 2021, property prices in suburbs closer to CBD are generally higher. The median prices begin to drop off passed 40 km (about 1 hour drive).

It was noticed that sale prices for Houses were significantly higher than Units within 30 km from Sydney CBD. Whereas prices for Units appeared to be far less affected by the distance.

CBD Suburnbs vs Outskirts¶

In this section, property sales within 35 km of Sydney CBD were further analyzed, for convenience, these suburbs were named CBD Suburbs while those outside of this range is named Outskirts.

Among all suburbs, only 19.1% of them are considered outskirts.

While property price for both CBD suburbs and outskirts grow similarly, it was noticed that House in the outskirts were sold at price comparable to Units in the CBD suburbs.

Price growth rate in each CBD suburb¶

Being new immigrants with little local knowledge, in order to select suburbs with blooming market, it is of interest to find localities with highest annual growth rate in property price.

To gauge the price increments on each CBD suburbs, a linear regression model was fitted on data of each locality. As an approximation, it was assumed that the annual rate of change of price is constant (i.e. price increase every year in a constant rate), the price model is therefore:

$$price = e^{m(year)+c}$$

where m, c are regression coefficients and that annual rate of change of price is: $$ rate = e^m$$

To maintain sensible outcomes from regression models, note that only suburbs with properties sales in at least 9 years from 2000 to 2021 were considered. In total, 410 out of 436 CBD suburbs matches this criteria. Note that among these suburbs, in order to obtain sensible results, regression models were fitted only if there are more than 9 years with sales for each property type (House or Unit).

Regression results suggested that annual growth rate for both Houses and Units are normally distributed. Houses generally see higher growth rate with mean of 6.4% and standard deviation of 1.8%, while that for Units are mean of 5.1% and s.d. of 1.2%.

Suburbs with highest growth rate¶

With regression applied, suburbs with highest growth rates in both Houses and Units were plotted below as references.

House¶

Price trends for CBD suburbs with highest growth rate in Houses were provided in Fig. 8. It appears that in these regions, the price gaps between Houses and Units have grown substantially over the last 21 years.

Unit¶

Price trends for CBD suburbs with highest growth rate in Units were provided in Fig. 9. In these regions, both Houses and Units saw price growth at similar rate, unlike the increasing price gaps for suburbs with high house price growth observed in Fig. 8.

Unit properties, number of bedrooms¶

In this section, property prices of Units with different number of bedrooms were analyzed. Note that only CBD suburbs were considered.

In general, more bedrooms imply higher median price.

As revealed in Fig. 11, majority (55.9%) of the Units sold were 2-bedrooms, with Units of 1-3 bedrooms constitude 97.6% of all the properties.

For reference, price trends of suburbs with highest growth rate in 2 bedrooms Units were plotted below. To focus on main-stream properties, note that only Units with 1-3 bedrooms were considered.

As shown in Fig. 12, while 1-bedroom and 3-bedrooms Units are not always available, their price trend were comparable to that of 2-bedrooms.

Summary¶

This exploratory analysis reveals the general price trend of the property market in Sydney. Suburbs with different distance from CBD were also studied with comparisons of price trends in Houses and Units. Later section focused on Units of suburbs closed to the CBD for personal interest.

Despite being a brief overview several insights were extracted:

  • Property prices consistently grow annually, with rate higher than that of the Consumer Price Index (CPI) of 3-4% in general (source).

  • Houses' prices have seen far more significant growth rate compared to units.

    • If able to afford, buying houses appears to be more profitable.

  • Median prices for houses near CBD are well outside of our budget. However, it was revealed in Fig. 6 that houses in the outskirts are priced comparably with units in CBD.

    • It may be worthwhile to buy a unit for convenince at work, and trade in with a house for retirement.

  • In CBD suburbs, majority of units sold in 2021 are 2-bedrooms.

    • This could aid our property search, knowing what is "main-stream".

Moving forwards, more dataset (e.g. crime rate statistics, rail station proximity, etc.) could be introduced to enhance understanding of the profile of each suburb.

On the other hand, it could be benificial to create a dashboard for this dataset, so as to investigate different aspects more liberally.
